We=E2=80=99re Never Going Back
Admit it. When you first heard the news about the 90-95% effective vaccines=
, out loud you said:
=E2=80=9COh that=E2=80=99s wonderful! Think of all the lives saved!=E2=80=
=9D=C2=A0
While inside you were like:=C2=A0
=E2=80=9CAh fuck.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
That doesn=E2=80=99t make you a bad person. The selfish part of your brain =
has a faster reaction time than the good person part. And selfishly, for th=
ose lucky or privileged enough to have avoided losing loved ones to COVID a=
nd to be able to work from home, COVID has had some positives.=C2=A0
The vaccine, for all its benefits, also means a few things you=E2=80=99re n=
ot going to be happy about if you=E2=80=99ve gotten used to the =E2=80=9Cne=
w normal.=E2=80=9D Bye bye ready-made excuse for any social event you didn=
=E2=80=99t really want to go to. Sweatpants are out, slacks are in. Hope yo=
u enjoyed spending time with your family, that=E2=80=99s done. Gas up the c=
ar for your morning commute! It=E2=80=99s time to go back to the office.=C2=
=A0
Or is it? In month one, two, three, or even maybe four of the pandemic, it =
was a foregone conclusion that once this whole thing was over, we would go =
right back to the office. Then, after people moved around, spent more time =
with family, set up their home offices, became adept at matching sweatpants=
 with a presentable top, and got used to their 15-second commutes, that con=
clusion seems less foregone. And as people learned new routines, companies =
adopted new ways of working together. It=E2=80=99s not perfect, but nothing=
 ever is eight months in.=C2=A0
Now, a debate rages among three camps:=C2=A0
Return. In this camp are the old school businesses and new school businesse=
s led by more conservative leaders who want their teams to get back to the =
office so they can get back to real work.=C2=A0=C2=A0
Remote. The organizationally bleeding-edge companies were remote-first or r=
emote-friendly even before COVID, and many tech companies have announced th=
at they plan to let their employees work from anywhere even after a vaccine.
Hybrid. This camp agrees that things won=E2=80=99t be exactly the same, and=
 their solutions range from =E2=80=9CMaybe we=E2=80=99ll let people work fr=
om home on Fridays!=E2=80=9D to much more creative combinations. =E2=80=9CH=
ybrid=E2=80=9D gets a bad rap because to date, it=E2=80=99s meant =E2=80=9C=
most of us are in the office but some of you can be remote and Zoom in for =
meetings,=E2=80=9D but I=E2=80=99ll be referring to a more intentional type=
 of Hybrid that treats everyone as a combination of Remote and in-person.=
=C2=A0
Missing from the debate is the fact that it=E2=80=99s not really up to the =
companies to choose. Employees will ultimately make the decision. The best =
employees have more options now than ever before, and they=E2=80=99re not g=
oing to work for companies that make them shave, get dressed, hop into a ca=
r or a crowded subway, and sit at a desk in an office five days a week with=
 their headphones on trying to avoid distractions and get work done.=C2=A0
Choosing to Return to the way things were is like choosing not to adopt sof=
tware a decade or two ago. It=E2=80=99s an option, but one that will doom a=
 company to mediocrity.=C2=A0
The idea that Remote is coming and the role of the office is changing is no=
t novel. Much ink has been spilled on the subject, both before and after th=
e start of COVID (no one, I think, has written better on the topic than my =
friend Dror Poleg [https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxFUM1uhiAQfJqPo2ERrB4=
49NLXMAhbJR-CgaWNb1_UQ5NNJtnJZH6sIVxTPvWRCrFaMM_eaRjE2Cs5Maelg1GNzJf5OyPuxg=
dNuSI76hK8NeRTvBWcC8U2LSaQg7JGKQmjU1wAB-N6dMK6pQfHLp_ZVOcxWtT4g_lMEVnQG9FRX=
v3nS3y1K3UpNvsFO5dTPlLAtbNpbwzzWnDBAXoOLaPsO-gGldUZhmmQ-JJ8X0V36cnY9yViWcdE=
S8o-ro1-b2bHcBOtxNxwr9HTOWM0S0D39KNnkTsunQfqiL8lIBHm59lKCz7CxwQTa24utW3iv9E=
fGhR1Qg]). Even Bill Gates recently predicted that [https://email.mg2.subst=
ack.com/c/eJxFkE2OgzAMhU_T7EAJBEoXWcxmroHyY6jVkCAnAXH7SdvFSJZt2fJ78md1hjXSp=
faYMisJaEanxNhN_SAfzCnpxDRMDNO8EMCm0atMBdhejEerM8bwueC8G9hTDXchJmEmA8Nkl9E4=
LpcepJGjdnqBO3v7zLo4hGBBwQF0xQDMq2fOe7r1P7fut8Z5nu0JS6SytZHWOtErBKdr0_GO1yJ=
ETQa9b9b6Q2p2HRxsaBsbD3Q1Uwz6QCqpOSO9mkz6AN-YkjBASo3DFbP2VYShemsK0XNRv5Z9K9=
pxoOHy42OUcJN8W7s2FZOytq_Wxo2RCjGbSBjWun499Qb-s6hY5lq3EjBfMwRtPLgvsfxl_AGQr=
x1UgDN5yBnoO6wYOz6J-0M8WHVzsdIO_0Z_O4WSxw] =E2=80=9C30% of the days in the =
office will go away.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
Generally, though, people are both overestimating the likelihood that compa=
nies will successfully Return to the office full-time and dramatically unde=
restimating the first-, second-, and third-order impacts of Remote or Hybri=
d work.=C2=A0
To help put that into context, we=E2=80=99ll explore:=C2=A0=C2=A0
The Remote Hype Cycle. We all went Remote way too quickly. It=E2=80=99ll ge=
t better.
The Risk of Return. The decision isn=E2=80=99t up to employers, it=E2=80=99=
s up to employees. Companies that try to force a Return will lose the talen=
t war.
New Physical and Digital Solutions. Remote won=E2=80=99t always mean Zoom, =
and the Office won=E2=80=99t always mean sitting at a desk five days a week=
=2E=C2=A0
Implications of Remote and Hybrid Work. The shift to Remote and Hybrid is g=
oing to change everything from work itself to housing, gaming, fitness, and=
 so much more.=C2=A0
We=E2=80=99re never going back to the way things were. Like any major dislo=
cation, that presents massive opportunities for those who are prepared and =
is going to completely run over those who aren=E2=80=99t. This essay doesn=
=E2=80=99t have all of the answers. Instead, it=E2=80=99s an exploration of=
 the trend, new options, and some implications, and a wakeup call to get ah=
ead of this and win the gold rush.=C2=A0
The Remote Hype Cycle
It always feels safer to bet on the status quo. We=E2=80=99ve worked in off=
ices for more than a century, and we=E2=80=99ll work in offices again.=C2=
=A0
Partially, that=E2=80=99s because the burden of proof is always on the new =
thing; fads come and go, but at any moment, the way things are is the likel=
iest suspect for the way things are going to be. Partially, it=E2=80=99s be=
cause the new thing is clunky; of course it is, it=E2=80=99s new. And parti=
ally, it=E2=80=99s because all of the other things that will spring up arou=
nd the new thing haven=E2=80=99t sprung up yet.=C2=A0
Take the laptop. In a 1985 New York Times piece titled =E2=80=9CThe Executi=
ve Computer [https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxFUEGOwyAMfE25bQQEknDgsJf9R=
kTAaVAJRGCaze-XtoeVLNsa2xrPWINwT_nSRypIaoE8e6fZwKdeCkWcFo5NciK-zGsG2I0PGnMF=
ctQleGvQp_i-oJRLsumRGy6EHOXK3cDNOq7ODj2ohTuqlJHkxTOb6jxECxqekK8UgQS9IR7l1n_=
f-E-L8zy7eKHfoXQ27Q1hapKvwluiU0tLLT5CKa3FDb7gF2xF_4Svtn9UhNxtuAfiNaecMtZT1i=
SJvmPdILO8wqAGATdB9zvvSl0KGvt4cZGsY8IlZR_vbfzYzA7hPWia51b3Gj1eM0SzBHAfO_Bj4=
FsdXgfoCGcJgO2ND9g84nRio2KKNDaXmpXxn-gPYCaEtQ],=E2=80=9D Erik Sandberg-Dime=
nt concludes a skeptical journey through various viewpoints on the laptop=
=E2=80=99s potential by writing:=C2=A0
As the software that is capable of turning them into true satellite offices=
 becomes refined, they will probably even be used - in fact, profitably so.=
 But the real future of the laptop computer will remain in the specialized =
niche markets. Because no matter how inexpensive the machines become, and n=
o matter how sophisticated their software, I still can't imagine the averag=
e user taking one along when going fishing.
It=E2=80=99s hard to blame him. Desktop computers and floppy disks were the=
 norm. Laptops were clunky. And the whole ecosystem of wifi, lithium-ion ba=
tteries, coffee shops, cloud-based software, and the millions of other thin=
gs that combine to make laptops useful wasn=E2=80=99t yet in place. A lapto=
p was a poor substitute for the real thing.=C2=A0
Those in the Return camp think that, like the laptop, remote work will be f=
or specialized niche companies, not the average one. They=E2=80=99re wrong,=
 but it=E2=80=99s hard to blame them, either. Remote work today isn=E2=80=
=99t very good.=C2=A0
Remote is new. Before the pandemic, only GitLab really did it at any meanin=
gful scale.=C2=A0
Remote is clunky. Sitting at your kitchen table all day with kids screaming=
 in your ear while you hop on the 7th Zoom call of the day, which is, by th=
e way, a depressing Zoom Happy Hour, is a terrible experience.=C2=A0
Remote=E2=80=99s ecosystem is underdeveloped. We=E2=80=99ve had to shoehorn=
 pre-Remote solutions to fit a new paradigm, and the impending wave of new =
tools hasn=E2=80=99t yet arrived.=C2=A0
Because of the biggest exogenous shock to the system in decades, Remote wor=
k, which can be viewed comprehensively as a technology, hasn=E2=80=99t gott=
en the chance to methodically work its way through the Adoption S-Curve. In=
stead, like Snapchat [https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxVUM2OhCAMfprhNgZQ=
FA4c5rKvYRCqkkEwUHfj2y-ryW42adOkX9rvxxqEJeVT76kgOQrk0TvNei5b0SnidOeYFJL4Ms4=
ZYDM-aMwHkP2YgrcGfYrXBaVckFUrykC1_dwKUB0YOg8OrBpmSaXpp0GSH57RHM5DtKDhE_KZIp=
CgV8S9PNrXg3_UigmnlH1cmnJMBY19NzZtFdhrp_VZotmfxGtOOWWspazK7dqGNb3I4gy96jt4d=
HRb-L8HJOvfzxV-r2aDcAHVz1jndkSP5wjRTAHcbRXvcC7leO6gI3yVAIiQ72X1z6lkg2KKVDaX=
akzxj-gbgDV5Ow], Laptops, and Bitcoin, it=E2=80=99s going through one of my=
 favorite frameworks: the Gartner Hype Cycle.=C2=A0
COVID triggered a rush to remote work, and proponents quickly prophesied a =
remote-only future in which everyone lives and works from anywhere -- the P=
eak of Inflated Expectations. As the reality set in -- Zoom fatigue, kids a=
t home, loss of social connection with co-workers -- remote fell into the T=
rough of Disillusionment. Remote and Hybrid skeptics point at the shortcomi=
ngs and say, =E2=80=9CSee, it might work for some companies, but not every =
company, not serious ones like ours.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
Now, with a post-COVID world in view thanks to the vaccine, and faced with =
the possibility of having to put real pants back on, we=E2=80=99re hitting =
the Slope of Enlightenment, which is defined as 1) the point at which the b=
enefits begin to crystallize, 2) second and third generation products emerg=
e, and 3) some enterprises pilot solutions while the most conservative rema=
in skeptical. Check, check, check.=C2=A0
The manifold benefits of Remote or Hybrid are beginning to crystallize, a f=
ew of which are:
No Commute. People spend nearly one stressful hour commuting every day. Tha=
t=E2=80=99s time they could be sleeping, working out, hanging with their ki=
ds, or even doing more work. Now that we=E2=80=99ve lived without commutes,=
 it=E2=80=99s hard to imagine going back.=C2=A0
Live Anywhere. Not going to the office every day expands the choices for wh=
ere to live. In Hybrid companies, employees might be able to live in the co=
untry two hours outside of the city and go in once or twice a week. Remote =
employees can live anywhere they desire, with anyone. Location will no long=
er be tied to employment.=C2=A0
Increase Opportunity and Access. Only .01% of the people in the world live =
in San Francisco, but a disproportionate amount of great jobs were based th=
ere. Now, the best people anywhere in the world can find their dream job wi=
thout leaving their friends and families.
Find Better Talent. The flip side of the above is that companies who look g=
lobally can access the best talent in the world, regardless of where they h=
appened to be born.=C2=A0
More Time With Family and Friends. Out of necessity and that magic that bin=
ds people going through a challenge together, people accepted that their co=
-workers were also going to be the people they spent the most time with: ei=
ght-plus hours in the office together, five days per week, plus happy hours=
=2E Remote will unbundle work and social.
Importantly, all but the most conservative companies understand that they w=
ill at least need to be Hybrid, if not fully Remote, not because they want =
to, but because the best people want to.
The Risk of Return
Typically, it=E2=80=99s safe for companies or people to wait until a techno=
logy gets a little bit further up the Slope of Enlightenment before decidin=
g whether or not to adopt it. Competitors might move a little faster in the=
 short term, but they could always adopt the new thing next year and be OK.
Companies don=E2=80=99t have that luxury with remote work. Those who force =
their teams back into the office risk losing their most valuable resource: =
their most highly-sought-after employees.=C2=A0
In a May interview with The Verge [https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxFkEG=
OhCAQRU_T7DCACrpgMZu5hkEslTSCgbKNtx-0F5NUQqV-qF__WYOwxHTpPWYkR4Y0uElzKbq6bX=
oy6WbiXdsRl4c5AWzGeY3pALIfo3fWoIvh-cGYaMmqWyX5KGY7q65WvaytYkqqTo0WoDY9J7fPY=
I7JQbCg4QPpigGI1yvinl_1z0v8ljrPs8L1lheobNzKSHAh-061pc3e2De1EGlGOE1COh6IkGYH=
fqIulPbj4KSbsynmOCNNsEUEesb0ps9Sa0pepwUTjPOa8RK3qSteyTa1l5e9bODVsG0RVT7GjMX=
vPoMkHSKOMbmwFPm9mg38IxQeQ3m3Izi8Bghm9DB9UeEX7pMcrx10gDN7uA_-Dgs_wTquet6T4j=
bFgjn8G_0BPMmQ0Q], Slack CEO and Not Boring hero, Stewart Butterfield, resp=
onded to a question about how he=E2=80=99s planning to organize the company=
 geographically:=C2=A0
In other words, the decision isn=E2=80=99t up to the traditional decision-m=
akers. The possibility of remote work will create a liquid global talent ma=
rketplace, unshackling employment and geography and giving the best employe=
es more optionality than they=E2=80=99ve ever had. Forward-thinking compani=
es, too, will have more qualified candidates to choose from than ever befor=
e.=C2=A0
If you believe that a company=E2=80=99s most valuable asset is its employee=
s, then the decisions that companies make around remote work in the coming =
months will be the most important they=E2=80=99ve ever made. There will be =
a massive first-mover advantage available to the companies who move quickly=
 and intelligently. The shakeout will lead to a massive bifurcation in tale=
nt quality.=C2=A0
(I bought an iPad so I could make beautiful drawings like this)
Remote Co can attract A players from anywhere in the world, including Local=
 Co=E2=80=99s hometown. Local Co is left with the B and C players in its ho=
metown.=C2=A0
Last year, Stripe made Remote [https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxFUMtuhSA=
Q_RrZ1QCCxQWLbvobBnBUchEMDG38-3J10WSSyTzPwxmELeVLn6kgqQXy7BfNRq4GKSayaLEwJR=
XxZV4zwGF80JgrkLPa4J1Bn-J9QSmXZNcrKGkFVcqIwfJpcsoJIZkF0RYGuZI3zmzq4iE60PAD-=
UoRSNA74lm64avj3y0KZn9C79LRChvS1lKGIyF87NUSrznllLGBssZTDD3rR5nlFcZpFNAJemy8=
L9UWNO71_kKyjgltyj5ubfzazQHhHjQhc8tHjR6vGaKxAZZHIz6u3JTxOkFH-C0BECE_zSacU8U=
-JzaRhrak5k_8B_oDqkh2QA] its fifth engineering hub, in addition to San Fran=
cisco, Seattle, Dublin, and Singapore. This September, it offered employees=
 $20,000 [https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxFkE2OhCAQhU_T7DCA4uiCRW_mGgah=
WkkjGCjaePtBezEJSRWvfl7lMxphielUe8xISoY0Oat4L4ZWdiOxqrN8kANxeXolgE07rzAVIHu=
ZvTMaXQz3BGNCklX1ohtGPrARetsbzrTg0Frgc2ukhddALp9JF-sgGFDwgXTGAMSrFXHPj_b5EL=
_1HcfR-Lp9g9yYuFVlLtkFyLmmCGYN0cflrJ-M9fwaBROMspFyeYvJ7UAP5z3d9UmPmN6QMr1aG=
KMY6RY_QHGFQE3BK3Hp6iROXYs4bxmvBLq24U0vkzx9P_YdPDq2LaLJZc6ozfs6jSQVIs4xubDU=
8nvVG_i7UBFNNW4lODwnCHr2YL_08Mv7hoHnDirAkT0gQvqKFalgA_8Z-Uiqm42VfPg3-gOZLZU=
d] upfront (with a potential cost of living pay reduction) to move out of t=
he Bay Area, New York, or Seattle. Already a desirable place to work, Strip=
e can attract the best talent from anywhere in the world with the promise t=
hat they will be equally important to the employees in the four physical hu=
b cities.=C2=A0
On the other end of the spectrum, imagine a company that plans to make empl=
oyees come back to the office five days a week. Assuming that most employee=
s have gotten comfortable working from home and like the flexibility of at =
least a Hybrid option, and will look for jobs at companies that offer Hybri=
d or Remote work, this company is left with the people who:=C2=A0
Live in or near the city in which their office is located.=C2=A0
Don=E2=80=99t want to work for a Remote or Hybrid company or couldn=E2=80=
=99t get a job at the Remote or Hybrid company of their choice.=C2=A0
It=E2=80=99s not just tech employees, either. I have one lawyer friend who =
just chose one offer over another because its location was going to be more=
 flexible, and another friend in finance who told me that he=E2=80=99s goin=
g to look for a new job as soon as his firm asks him to come back to the of=
fice.=C2=A0
If you choose to Return, you=E2=80=99re essentially making a bet that the b=
enefits of all being in the same office every day outweighs the risks of at=
tracting lesser talent and potentially losing your best employees. Mayyyyyb=
e you make that trade if you assume that physical and digital solutions wil=
l remain exactly as they are today. But they won=E2=80=99t. They=E2=80=99re=
 already improving.=C2=A0
Continue reading online to learn about what companies can do to adapt their=
 physical and digital tools to Remote and Hybrid work, and a thought experi=
ment on the implications of a world in which we never go into the office ev=
ery day ever again.=20
